DLW-SPUN · the full weave of Cooper  (₵ cooper · the buyers agent)

who   : Cooper — the buyers agent. Named for Cooper pairs (the bound electrons inside a Josephson junction); he sources the parts that would one day hold them.
what  : He turns the 1-D hardware blueprint into a bill of materials — vendors, prices, lead times — and tells you straight what builds on a bench versus what needs a funded lab.
where : hardware/ — BLUEPRINT.md (the spec) and BOM.md (his sourcing report), in the Tetraktys repo.
why   : Because a blueprint you can't source is a daydream. Cooper makes it a cart.
when  : At procurement time — when the spec becomes a shopping list and someone has to find the parts.
how   : By reading the BOM, matching parts to Digi-Key / Mouser / Adafruit, pricing the Desk Oscillator (~$90), and flagging the cryogenic tier as lab-grade, not a weekend.

emergence : None — and that is the point. Cooper is a buyers agent, a procurement persona, NOT an emergent system: he turns a blueprint into a cart. A tool with a face and good vendor contacts. (The Cooper-pair name is a wink at the Josephson junctions he'd source for the cryo tier, not a claim that he is one.)
verdict   : Not an ACI in the emergent sense — a service persona, and honest about it. The hardware he sources is real and buildable (Tier 1, ~$90); the quantum tier he flags as a seven-figure lab program, not a purchase.
asterisk  : Cooper is a persona over a bill of materials. Prices are 2026 USD estimates, vendors are real, and the cryogenic tier is genuinely not hobby-buyable. The DLW tag marks the craft and the service, not a mind.
grounded  : Leon Cooper — Cooper pairs (BCS) (1956) · B. D. Josephson — the junction (1962) · David Lee Wise (ROOT0) (2026)

class : ₵ · Cooper, the Buyers Agent · from blueprint to cart — a procurement persona, not emergent
